< review>
Overturned Denial of Long Term Disability Claim

After a stressful filing and follow-up, my long-term disability claim was denied. The stress from dealing with the insurance company was overwhelming. Just when I was going to give up,¬†¬†with only 30 days left to file an appeal,¬†I found Kantor & Kantor online.

Shortly after the intake meeting, I met with Mr. Kantor to go over my case. He explained how his team would proceed with my case. I felt so relieved to know that there were people who could help me in this case. Throughout the next few months, Mr. Kantor's team worked very closely with me to get all the documents submitted as needed.

Finally, thanks to all the hard work from Mr. Kantor and his dedicated team, my LTD denial claim was overturned. Without their help, I would never have received any benefits from the insurance company.¬† For that, I am very grateful.

I highly recommend Kantor & Kantor to everyone who is having trouble with their STD or¬† LTD claims.< /review>

<Text>I found Kantor & Kantor through a google search when I was desperately looking for help after an insurance company (offered through my employer) was withholding disability pay from me. I wasn‚Äôt expecting to hear back any time soon considering that the stay at home order due to COVID-19 was just put in place that week and I assumed that people weren‚Äôt in the office or they were not accepting new clients at this time. It wasn‚Äôt even an hour or so later that Glenn Kantor himself gave me a call to talk and find out more about how he could help me.

In short, I was diagnosed with Multiple Sclerosis and because of my most recent relapse, I‚Äôd been left with some symptoms that made it impossible for me to work. I am a financial advisor for a very well-known firm and I never thought that I would find myself in a position where I needed help this urgently. My insurance company wanted to stop paying me the week my employer would no longer be responsible for my pay and they would have to take over. <user_id>113952563499830631249</user_id><username>Merisa M< /username><date>1479249518367< /date>< Rating>
1</Rating>
< review>
I like to consider myself as an experienced club go-er, not that I'm bragging about how many nights out I've had, but I think I know a good club when I see one.  This, however, is not a good club.  I've been to Social twice.  Once was during a night of club hoppping when a group of us had a party bus and the second was this past weekend for a friend's birthday. Both times I've gone, I felt like a sardine stuffed into an overly full sardine can.  It's not that this place is super packed with people (because, trust me, this place isn't that popular), but the dance floor is ridiculously small so it just feels crowded.

Pretty much, if you think of the layout of the club as a big rectangle, around the perimeter are VIP tables and booths.  In the middle is a big wrap around bar, and then on the far edges inbetween the bar and the VIP tables is the dance floor.  Seriously, my bedroom is bigger than the space provided for dancing.  Of all my nights outs, I've never been stepped on so many times before to the point that I have bruises from drunk girls who can't hold it together.

To top it off, even if you're on guestlist for Social, if you don't make it to the register in time, they make you pay $20.  This place is not worth $20.  Atleast at The Park, if you're on guestlist, despite their cutoff time, you get a discounted rate of only $5 instead of $15.

My Recommendations: if you want to have a great time, a spacious dancefloor to get your groove on (without having to worry about some drunk spilling a drink on you), and a more upscale club experience, hit up The Park Ultra Lounge instead.  Straight up, this place just reaffirmed why I love the Park so much.</review>

Faith's philosophy, a mix of political correctness and prosperity gospel. As I attended the main service I observed a repetitive message; you deserve by hoping mixed with cajoling for money. An exploit of impulsive compassion. A message to mute careful reasoning and activate undifferentiated empathy. Hope and optimism while demonizing any reality that causes stress.  Tithing profits bleed from the housing bubble and currently the education bubble is encouraged to self destructive excess.

A common expectation that leads to bitterness with this church is you will be helped in your time of need. This bitterness is exacerbated by the pastoral staffs conspicuous consumption, leisure and cosmetic augmentation, real or fabricated, while aggressively encouraging donations. A prudent way to view this is your paying for a show; that's it and nothing more. Countless testimonials have proven help will never come from this church.

Entitlement thinking without sacrifice and hard work is effective in exploiting others, we are what we do. Political correctness is very toxic to young boys. <Rate>1</Rate><user_id>111955968943549161981< /user_id><date>1391665317179<//date><gmap_id>0x80c3281f1546f027:0x2ebf6f3e098d7516<//gmap_id><review>I wanted to like this church, I really did.

Because of that, I gave it a fair shake by attending numerous services over half a year.

Right off the bat, the worship team rocked with some great contemporary praise and worship music. Hats off to that team and their passion.

Unfortunately, there were a few warning signs about the church that set my spiritual Spidey Sense tinglin'.

Dr. Jim seems nice enough, but most of his sermons are more geared towards that self-help topical format, without enough Biblical references. I felt that if I attended this church regularly, I likely wouldn't learn much about the Bible that I didn't already know. Milk rather than meat.

His sermons are also devoid of much reference to sin, repentance and the consequences. That usually to me is another big red flag.

The straw that broke the proverbial camel's back was when he played a video from Joel Osteen. Any discerning, mature Christian knows that the criticisms of Osteen are valid. His prosperity health and wealth gospel is a false gospel that classifies him as a false teacher to me. And any church that endorses and aligns themselves with Osteen cannot be trusted.

I left on that day and never came back.

California has a trend towards these megachurches and celebrity pastors. I urge Christians and non-believers to seek out smaller churches that are solidly rooted in the Bible.

As for me, I'm currently attending West Covina Christian Church now and find it to be a much more godly church led by mature pastors who preach heavily from the Scriptures.< /review><Name>Edward M. Yang</Name><resp>None< /resp>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

<userid>105071188506062505869</userid><user_name>Keith-Curtis<//user_name>< time>
1623045600136< /time>
<Rating>5</Rating>< review>
I recently purchased a new car and was anxious about where I would get my windows tinted. My experience with Jet Black was pretty stellar.

1) I called the (510) phone # and spoke to an agent who got me scheduled in less than 5 minutes (also was stoked to discover this location here in San Fran.

2) Showed up and was greeted by the branch manager, Ibrahim, who showed me the different tints, a visual/physical demonstration with a heat lamp to show climate response, and a total.

3) Walked over to Gus's Community Market 3 blocks away where you can sit outside and enjoy coffee or pass by the time (which is amazing because Jet Black does not have a seating/waiting area).

4) Returned 2 hours later to an awesome job.

Cost ended up around 350 tax included-- keep in mind I chose the Ceramic tint versus the other tints (which looked also pretty stellar).

Overall, amazing job to Ibrahim and the staff. Appreciate your services both in the detail as well as making the process as a customer enjoyable.< /review>

<review>In my opinion, Tomi is the best sushi spot in the Bay Area.
When we moved from Mountain View to SF, we expected to find our sushi spot. Instead, we found that none of them have quite compared to Tomi. Either the sushi was fantastic but too expensive, or the prices were decent but the fish to rice ratio was terrible or the quality of the fish was lacking.
What really sets Tomi apart is their customer service. Personally, I love their first come, first serve approach. Though it can get quite busy during peak hours, it‚Äôs always worth the wait. Plus, the nicest people you‚Äôll ever meet will greet and serve you. Each server at Tomi is kind, attentive, and ensures that you leave smiling. This is the type of spot that once you visit 3 times, they know who you are and begin to greet you by name.
During COVID, Tomi quickly adjusted to take out dining. When in person dining began again, they adjusted again to make you feel safe dining inside (seating very limited tables well apart, instituting contract tracing, ensuring patrons followed mask rules, etc.).
Overall, I cannot recommend this spot enough. It‚Äôs a gem! Special thank you to the Tomi team for always making us feel welcome. You guys are amazing and we love visiting you!< /review><user>107546455738801359501<//user>< resp>

The place's ambiance is pretty hipster. It's a good place for a date. They have good vegan options. I liked the quote that they had by Mother Theresa. One recommendation I would make, is that the restaurant needs to come up with a new to-go system. There was a line in the restaurant for to-go and it was annoying at times when the line would reach our table. We noticed that a lot of the tables were waiting a long time for their food. <review>Finally got to come here after wanting to for over a year. We ordered lunch take out. The maguro, sake, and hamachi sashimi that is listed on the dinner menu is available for lunch! We ordered that and their seasonal bluefin toro, kanpachi, and hirame nigiri. Fish is extremely fresh. Sashimi slices are also nice and thick! Not those flimsy small bites you get elsewhere. I'd definitely come here again in the near future. This meal was close to 100$ after tax and tip but it fed 3 people.

The ordering is restricted to take out right now. I highly recommend calling right when they open and then showing up 30ish after to pick up. There were people in line for pick up when I got there at 11:40am on a Tuesday. I placed my order at 11:25am and left the restaurant and 11:55am. There is just one lady running phones, shipping out orders, and taking in person orders so it's a bit slow but this can't be helped im the pandemic. If you're willing to wait a bit, or phone in early, it's worth it!</review>< Rate>
5</Rate>

<UserId.>102134706380163218845</UserId.>< text>
This sushi restaurant is excellent and it‚Äôs the most popular in Mountain View for a reason! It‚Äôs a little out of the way looking - definitely not what I expected at first brush, but the food is incredible and they give you great portion sizes.
I would say the one downside is that because it has such a popular reputation there‚Äôs a line out of the door pretty much any day of the week. The line is first-come first-serve, so for example I went at 7 pm on a Tuesday and still had to wait 40 minutes to seat a party of two.
That aside, the price is reasonable, the wait staff is (very) attentive (since they‚Äôre trying to seat so many people they prefer you order quickly), and it‚Äôs worth the wait; definitely a must try in Mountain View.</text>

< text>
I'm not a great fan of sushi (or any raw food items) but I try sushi once in a while..!
This restaurant is located slightly away from the castro street.
But noticed that it always has huge line of people waiting outside. I have  waited for almost 30 min to get seated.
It was difficult for me to order, because every item has some japanese name that I could not figure out whether it was raw or cooked. I looked at the table next to me and noticed this beautiful looking sushi and decided to try it.
I ordered that dish (spicy bomb -- Sushi fried and  served with spicy sauce) and loved it..!
Attached the photo.
Green Tea ice cream was also good.< /text>

Got the "Extra special chef's choice sushi set" and received a super high quality succulent set of sushi. A lot of other restaurants often give a good variety of fish types in a set like this, but usually none of the pricier items. <review>It's the best sushi spot that I've found so far in the lower peninsula.  It's our go to place down here.   They often have a line unless you come early.   If you don't come early, do takeout.   The sushi is always fresh.   They have a good variety.   Their Tomi special roll is very good - seared salmon and scallops on top of your choice of hamachi, salmon or spicy tuna filling.   The have all of the standard popular rolls and they're all pretty good.   The super bomb roll, fried spicy tuna roll, can be a bit dry.  Their omakase is reasonably priced.  They have Japanese beers on tap as well as a couple of other Japanese beers that are more uncommon.<//review><name>Dan Cheng< /name>< Response>
None</Response>

IMO, best sushi place in South Bay. Atmosphere is traditional Japanese, heavy on bamboo and light wood tones. <name>Luke L</name><GmapID>0x808fb73161d008c9:0xf1ccd9ca251ef04</GmapID>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< review>
I've been here several times now and have never been disappointed. The restaurant itself isn't super big and they have yet to integrate with Yelp waitlist, so you certainly should expect a bit of a wait.

Maybe that one punctual friend in your party can put his/her name down first while everyone else shows up 15-20 minutes late. That happened to me a few times, and while I didn't LOVE waiting by myself, at least nobody else had to wait -_-...

I am usually a man of habit, so most of the time I just order their sushi rolls. But last time I came, a friend ordered the hamachi kama and it was amazing. Ambrosian even. It was so fatty and so juicy, almost like butter melting in your mouth. I'd definitely recommend you to try that!</review>

< username>
Cosmo Wilson<//username>
<Rating>5<//Rating><Response>None< /Response><userid>100849072955957555399<//userid>< review>
Walk inside and put your name and how many in you party on their list. Choose if you want a table, the Sushi bar or either, and then head back outside and wait to be called.

Don't let the line fool you- it moves a lot quicker than you expect.

And once you get inside, you will find it was worth the wait, long or short. This place is buzzing! I was given a seat at the bar (my first choice) and was promptly asked for my drink order as I was seated- excellent! I was given a dinner menu and a paper Sushi menu with a pencil, alternatively I could order straight from the Sushi chefs; and a small bowl of Edamame. I ordered a draft beer and a large Sak√©.

For dinner, I ordered several pieces of Nigiri Sushi, as well as 3 rolls. about 15 minutes later I was served a beautifully displayed plate of fresh and tasty Sushi, and enjoyed it immensely.

I love sitting at the Sushi bar and watching the chefs do their amazing food-art, but it is also great seeing all the people come and go, and watching the servers organize a veritable symphony of getting people seated in a quick, but orderly fashion.

This place is loud and fun, food is excellent, and do NOT be put off by the amount of people outside- it's quicker than you think and worth the wait!</review>

< text>
This is the best authentic Japanese restaurant we know of in downtown Mountain View. They aren't terribly innovative or creative, just good traditional food. They have been there for a long time.

They are quite popular so a reservation or early arrival is advised. Also, don't do what I did and call the similarly named Tomi Sushi which is not the same restaurant.

There is a free public parking lot across the street. If that fills up, which it often does, you can generally find street parking in the neighborhood.< /text>

<user>100191831192041211945<//user>< Name>
chris chan</Name>
<date>1537924657799<//date><rate>5</rate>< Review>
Outstanding.

One of the best Japanese, if not, the best Japanese I've ever had. They take their craft seriously.

I have been five times since working in the area. Every time is amazing.

I have had the Special Chirashi on most occasions.  The chefs put together a nice spread. They really try to complement all the different textures and flavours.

As an interesting point, I normally do not like the pickled ginger in Japanese cuisine, but I realized it's because I've never had it as fresh and tasty as Tomi makes it. Their wasabi is also very fresh.

There is almost always a long line/wait to get in. They don't take reservations, but the wait is well worth it. You will NOT be disappointed.

Keep up the great work here.</Review>

<Review>Outstanding.

One of the best Japanese, if not, the best Japanese I've ever had. They take their craft seriously.

I have been five times since working in the area. Every time is amazing.

I have had the Special Chirashi on most occasions.  The chefs put together a nice spread. They really try to complement all the different textures and flavours.

As an interesting point, I normally do not like the pickled ginger in Japanese cuisine, but I realized it's because I've never had it as fresh and tasty as Tomi makes it. Their wasabi is also very fresh.

There is almost always a long line/wait to get in. They don't take reservations, but the wait is well worth it. You will NOT be disappointed.

Keep up the great work here.<//Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><response>None<//response><Gmap_id>0x808fb73161d008c9:0xf1ccd9ca251ef04</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<pictures>None<//pictures><user_name>Alyx Barranger< /user_name>< Review>
I had been reluctant to try Sushi Tomi since everyone had told me it is the BEST sushi in the bay so I had some seriously high expectations coming here.  I was in the area after the Mountain View Farmer's Market and decided it would be fun to grab a quick sushi snack here and try their sushi pieces.  I ordered salmon and red snapper, which I had never tried before.

The red snapper was incredibly unique - but in a delicious way, not in a euphemism for gross way.  The sushi chef suggested that I don't dip this in soy sauce to appreciate the flavors, and he definitely was right.  It was light and refreshing.  The

The salmon was out of this world, mouth-gasm inducing delicious.  It encompassed everything I had ever wanted from salmon, and I loved it so much that I had to order another.

Sushi Tomi hands down has the best fish in the bay.  I don't know if they would be a good fit if you are looking for fusion rolls since they have a more straight up, traditional sushi vibe, but if you just appreciate delicious sushi, you will love it here.</Review>

This was ok for the price, but I was a little disappointed given the really good reviews. Maybe we caught them on a bad night.

Got the Extra Special Nigiri. The tuna rolls were really good, but some of the other pieces were a little tough. The uni was really bad -- bitter and fishy. To make up for it, they gave us some ice cream on the house.

The place was packed even on a Tuesday, and other reviews are really good, so hopefully we just caught them on a bad night. I can't give more than a 3 for our visit, though.<//Text>

<UserId.>107968783541319464850<//UserId.>< pictures>
None< /pictures>
< date>
1376121085494< /date>
< text>
Sushitomi is the place to go for fresh fish in Mountain View. While menu items tend toward the pricier side, the quality of ingredients and preparation are distinctive. The restaurant is quite cozy, so be prepared to dine in close quarters. As Sushitomi does not accept reservations, waiting to be seated is basically a given upon arrival. One tip for prospective diners: if you don't mind jostling elbows, applying for a seat at the sushi counter may get in you faster. Service is prompt and polite, though may be slow at times when the restaurant is exceptionally busy.</text>

< Review>
My most favorite sushi place in the South Bay.

You can find anything from baby octopus, squid, abalone, and other special fishes in addition to the simple salmon and hamachi here. If in doubt, you can never go wrong with any of the daily specials.

The lunch specials are a steal for the freshness and portion size. There are usually 3 varieties - a kama (fish collar), curry, and sushi to choose from. It is accompanied by a salad, rice, and fish with veggies soup.</Review>

<time>1516856419112</time><Text>I have been to Sushi Tomi countless of times, and the sushi always meets the highest standards of quality. This is not a place to enjoy a broad menu of fantasy sushi rolls.  Instead, Tomi is a heaven for purists that cherish the range of flavors of the sea in all their subtlety, prepared in deceptively simple forms of sashimi and nigiri. To this end, the chefs make great use of local seafood and fish flown from Tsukiji, which makes me come back despite the wait and the crowded space. And I return again and again.< /Text>< Response>

< Review>
Came here for lunch.

Ordered the sashimi lunch combo.

Rice, tuna, salmon, yellowtail, and one more fish (don't recall).

Came out in a timely manner, fish tasted like it was lightly frozen, but otherwise delicious and fatty.

It was a bit odd that it came with hot rice, but to each their own I suppose.

This location is luckily located near the edge of downtown MVW, as it was brimming full during the lunch hour. Parking should be easier compared to other lunchspots.< /Review>

< Text>
Update 11/22/2017: dropping a star here. I went back a few weeks ago and was disappointed. The sushi was still good, but not as before. Their unagi-don was served on a round bowl and sort of thrown together, rather than the usual neat arrangement on a rectangular dish. Also, they didn't include the typical pickled veggies that usually come as condiments.

And their chicken karaage was a disaster. Do not get the chicken karaage here. So disappointing. It was just chicken wings, and only the bad part of the wing with almost no meat, and there was no flavor to it at all, just fried. It wasn't boneless, it wasn't tasty, it wasn't karaage.

I'm not planning to go back to this place anytime soon.< /Text>

< text>
The chirashi -- even the "regular" one -- is out of this world.  Fish melts in your mouth and is super-fresh, rice is outstandingly flavored, wasabi (very strong!) and ginger are perfect, and portion is very reasonable for the cost.  Seriously compares with the chirashi I had in Japan.

I ended up just getting it to go this time (it was ready 20 minutes after I phoned in my order).  Saves on having to deal with the very crowded restaurant, but you do miss out on the tea and such :\.<//text>

<Text>Incompetent service, mediocre sushi. $40 for FOUR pieces of sashimi?

When our (excellent) local sushi place in Los Altos had a problem with their delivery, we (sadly) turned to this place as an alternative using DoorDash.

Unfortunately Sushi Tomi messed up our order and--get this--wouldn't even admit their fault and essentially implied that we were trying to rip them off. In the end they tried to charge us $40 for FOUR pieces of sashimi (instead of the 14 we ordered), and they stuck to their story and wouldn't give an inch. They basically ruined our dinner plans and we had to supplement our it with things we cooked for ourselves.

The food we actually did get was mediocre at best. The fish wasn't very fresh, and the Dragon Roll was sloppily done and PACKED full of MAYONNAISE (yuck!).

For sushi delivery there are many more options. This restaurant clearly doesn't care about their customers.

Don't order from here unless you want to get your money taken from you, and/or you want your dinner plans destroyed, and/or you want sushi that isn't near as good as many other options nearby.<//Text><Pics>None<//Pics><username>Steve Thomas</username>< date>
1415734399384</date>

<Review>The line is long, and you think "this place must be great."  But, alas, you are wrong.

The place is underwhelming.  Edamame is free, but stale.  You can get better at Costco.

We ordered Sashimi special, sake toro, scallops, salmon roe, and uni.  Miso soup.  Green tea and Sapporo.    The only thing we liked were the scallops, miso, and tea/beer.  The rest was tough, dry, and dull.  One would expect better sushi at  your local supermarket.

I'm willing to give it another shot, if others in my party desire it.  But, honestly, given the higher cost/price, I'd go somewhere else.<//Review>< GmapID>

<user>108663260148567670950</user><name>Tyler Richendollar<//name>< date>
1495082481843< /date>
<rate>5< /rate>< Text>
Easily the best sushi in Mountain View if not the lower Peninsula. Their specials are often fresh-from-Tsukiji in Japan, and their execution is on point. We have gone five or so times, and we have yet to be disappointed by any aspect of their service or meals. We recommend the Chirashi for a medium-to-low priced meal, and the Omakase is unreal. Get the Omakase with two appetizers, and it will feed two comfortably. If going for rolls only, my wife always gets the mackerel and the uni. Really, most any choice, as long as it is predominantly fish and not a mish-mash, is going to be wonderful.

They take credit card, parking is tight, there's often a wait, and you have to sign-up on a list inside the door.<//Text>

- Low quality sushi (vs, say, Sushi Monster in Belmont)

+ good location,
+ decent authentic atmosphere (as compared to Sushi places in Tokyo, Osaka, and Okinawa)

Won't go back most likely.<//Review>

<gmap_id>0x808fb73161d008c9:0xf1ccd9ca251ef04<//gmap_id><user>103462788881784448122< /user><Rate>5< /Rate>< resp>

<pictures>None</pictures><name>Rafael L√©lis<//name></record>
</dataset><record>
<gmapID>0x808fb73161d008c9:0xf1ccd9ca251ef04<//gmapID><rate>5< /rate><UserId.>111939655073721219901</UserId.>< pics>
None<//pics>
< review>
Really nice little authentic Japanese restaurant tucked into the end of a shopping center on Apopka Vineland and John Young!

This place has high quality Japanese food and a warm and welcoming atmosphere!
*They have really good prices for lunch and reasonable prices for dinner.
Their grilled Mackeral is great (huge half of Mackerel with tail on). It has a great flavor and comes with grated radish, broccoli,  rice, and  miso soup or salad for $11 at lunch and $15 at dinner.  Same portion.
The salmon teriyaki is also really good and the teriyaki sauce is savory and not too sweet. It comes with potato salad, broccoli,  rice, and miso soup or salad for $10 lunch and $15 at dinner.  Portion maybe slightly smaller at lunch.

Their spicy tuna bowl is fantastic!! Chopped pieces of super fresh spicy tuna cover a massive bowl of sushi rice and comes with miso soup or salad for $11 lunch or $16 at dinner. You get a lot of tuna and the portion is the same at lunch and dinner.

At dinner time you get miso soup and house salad for the above dishes.

My favorite appetizer..... fried squid legs! So hot, cripsy, and chewy these things are to die for. They are not always on the white board but if you ask they always seem to have them.  ~$6
The sliced eggplant in garlic soy is also good. ~$6

One of my favorite Japanese restaurants in Orlando. Favorite Mackerel at Japanese restaurant in Orlando.

The ramen is good but not amazing like their fish dishes.

The pork katsudon is a great option if you prefer something other than seafood. It is a homestyle dish that is really filling and tasty for $11. A delicately fried pork cutlet with egg over rice with a lightly sweet soy type sauce. Hearty option.

Great local Japanese restaurant!</review>

<Name>Steve Thomas</Name><Date>1415734399384< /Date><rate>1<//rate>< Text>
Incompetent service, mediocre sushi. $40 for FOUR pieces of sashimi?

When our (excellent) local sushi place in Los Altos had a problem with their delivery, we (sadly) turned to this place as an alternative using DoorDash.

Unfortunately Sushi Tomi messed up our order and--get this--wouldn't even admit their fault and essentially implied that we were trying to rip them off. In the end they tried to charge us $40 for FOUR pieces of sashimi (instead of the 14 we ordered), and they stuck to their story and wouldn't give an inch. They basically ruined our dinner plans and we had to supplement our it with things we cooked for ourselves.

The food we actually did get was mediocre at best. The fish wasn't very fresh, and the Dragon Roll was sloppily done and PACKED full of MAYONNAISE (yuck!).

For sushi delivery there are many more options. This restaurant clearly doesn't care about their customers.

Don't order from here unless you want to get your money taken from you, and/or you want your dinner plans destroyed, and/or you want sushi that isn't near as good as many other options nearby.<//Text>

< Name>
Fred Brooks<//Name>
< time>
1489743968749</time>
<rating>5< /rating><review>Really nice little authentic Japanese restaurant tucked into the end of a shopping center on Apopka Vineland and John Young!

This place has high quality Japanese food and a warm and welcoming atmosphere!
*They have really good prices for lunch and reasonable prices for dinner.
Their grilled Mackeral is great (huge half of Mackerel with tail on). It has a great flavor and comes with grated radish, broccoli,  rice, and  miso soup or salad for $11 at lunch and $15 at dinner.  Same portion.
The salmon teriyaki is also really good and the teriyaki sauce is savory and not too sweet. It comes with potato salad, broccoli,  rice, and miso soup or salad for $10 lunch and $15 at dinner.  Portion maybe slightly smaller at lunch.

Their spicy tuna bowl is fantastic!! Chopped pieces of super fresh spicy tuna cover a massive bowl of sushi rice and comes with miso soup or salad for $11 lunch or $16 at dinner. You get a lot of tuna and the portion is the same at lunch and dinner.

At dinner time you get miso soup and house salad for the above dishes.

My favorite appetizer..... fried squid legs! So hot, cripsy, and chewy these things are to die for. They are not always on the white board but if you ask they always seem to have them.  ~$6
The sliced eggplant in garlic soy is also good. ~$6

One of my favorite Japanese restaurants in Orlando. Favorite Mackerel at Japanese restaurant in Orlando.

The ramen is good but not amazing like their fish dishes.

The pork katsudon is a great option if you prefer something other than seafood. It is a homestyle dish that is really filling and tasty for $11. A delicately fried pork cutlet with egg over rice with a lightly sweet soy type sauce. Hearty option.

Great local Japanese restaurant!< /review><pics>None<//pics>< response>
None< /response>

< username>
Jen H<//username>
<time>1423198002814<//time><rate>4</rate><Review>Probably my favorite place to get sushi in MV.

It's consistently good, portions are decent, and fish is fresh. It gets packed so make sure you beat the dinner/lunch crowd or you're waiting.

I highly recommend getting their sushi plates or their lunch/dinner combos. This place isn't too big on rolls so there's not a lot of options. I love their nigiri combos because it's the perfect amount of food and the fish is fresh and tasty! Their chirashi bowls also look good but that tends to be too much rice for me. Their lunch/dinner combos are actually pretty filling. I usually get the chicken terriyaki in combination with sashimi or spicy tuna roll. Their chicken is grilled just how I like it, which is to the point you can taste that charred/seared portion of the chicken and they don't go super heavy on the sauce which is nice!

Their prices are a higher than other sushi restaurants in the area but worth it if you're a fan of quality fish.< /Review><pictures>None<//pictures><resp>None<//resp><GmapID>0x808fb73161d008c9:0xf1ccd9ca251ef04</GmapID></record>
</dataset><record>

100366113117526980111< /user_id>
<pictures>None</pictures>< Review>
Probably my favorite place to get sushi in MV.

It's consistently good, portions are decent, and fish is fresh. It gets packed so make sure you beat the dinner/lunch crowd or you're waiting.

I highly recommend getting their sushi plates or their lunch/dinner combos. This place isn't too big on rolls so there's not a lot of options. I love their nigiri combos because it's the perfect amount of food and the fish is fresh and tasty! Their chirashi bowls also look good but that tends to be too much rice for me. Their lunch/dinner combos are actually pretty filling. I usually get the chicken terriyaki in combination with sashimi or spicy tuna roll. Their chicken is grilled just how I like it, which is to the point you can taste that charred/seared portion of the chicken and they don't go super heavy on the sauce which is nice!

Their prices are a higher than other sushi restaurants in the area but worth it if you're a fan of quality fish.<//Review>
